    "body": "### Problem\n\n`spell` is set as buffer-local instead of window-local when using `:setlocal`, even though `:h 'spell'` clearly defines `'spell'` as `local to window`.\n\n### Steps to reproduce\n\n- Run `nvim --clean`\n- `:setlocal spell`\n- Type an obvious typo, like \"dflkjlkjfsdgsd\"\n- Vim will correctly enable spell.\n- Open another buffer with `:e other`.\n- Type an obvious typo, like \"dflkjlkjfsdgsd\"\n- Spellcheck will not be on.\n\nCompare to:\n\n- Run `nvim --clean`\n- `:lua vim.wo.spell = true` instead.\n- Type an obvious typo, like \"dflkjlkjfsdgsd\"\n- Vim will correctly enable spell.\n- Open another buffer with `:e other`.\n- Type an obvious typo, like \"dflkjlkjfsdgsd\"\n- Spellcheck will work in the new buffer this time.\n\n(Note that setting `vim.bo.spell` is rejected by neovim)\n\n### Expected behavior\n\nI expect `spell` to be only window-local, as per the documentation.\n\nI would actually recommend changing `spell` from window-local to buffer-local, since all of the other `spell*` options are buffer local (`'spellcapcheck'`, `'spellfile'`, `'spelllang'`, and `'spelloptions'` are all documented as 'local to buffer'). If there's good reason for `'spell'` to work differently than the other options, it should at least be fixed. Otherwise, it should be changed to be local to buffer.\n\n### Nvim version (nvim -v)\n\nNVIM v0.11.4\n\n### Vim (not Nvim) behaves the same?\n\nyes, vim 9.1\n\n### Operating system/version\n\nFedora Linux\n\n### Terminal name/version\n\nkitty 0.42.2\n\n### $TERM environment variable\n\nxterm-kitty\n\n### Installation\n\nSystem Package Manager",
